        i0.ɵɵelementStart(189, "h3");
        i0.ɵɵtext(190, "Best practices for setting up your prototype");
        i0.ɵɵelementEnd();
        i0.ɵɵelementStart(191, "p")(192, "strong");
        i0.ɵɵtext(193, "Low fidelity or high fidelity?");
        i0.ɵɵelementEnd();
        i0.ɵɵtext(194, " Fidelity refers to how close a prototype will be to the real deal. If you\u2019re simply preparing a quick visual aid for a presentation, a low-fidelity prototype \u2014 like a wireframe with placeholder images and some basic text \u2014 would be more than enough. But if you\u2019re going for more intricate usability testing, a high-fidelity prototype \u2014 with on-brand colors, fonts and imagery \u2014 could help get more pointed results.");
        i0.ɵɵelementEnd();
        i0.ɵɵelementStart(195, "p")(196, "strong");
        i0.ɵɵtext(197, "Consider your user");
        i0.ɵɵelementEnd();
        i0.ɵɵtext(198, ". To create an intuitive user flow, try to think as your user would when interacting with your product. While you can fine-tune this during beta testing, considering your user\u2019s needs and habits early on will save you time by setting you on the right path.");
        i0.ɵɵelementEnd();
        i0.ɵɵelementStart(199, "p")(200, "strong");
        i0.ɵɵtext(201, "Start from the inside out");
        i0.ɵɵelementEnd();
        i0.ɵɵtext(202, ". A nice way to both organize your tasks and create more user-friendly prototypes is by building your prototypes \u2018inside out\u2019. Start by focusing on what will be important to your user, like a Buy now button or an image gallery, and list each element by order of priority. This way, you\u2019ll be able to create a prototype that puts your users\u2019 needs at the heart of your design.");
        i0.ɵɵelementEnd();
